http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 27 Nov 2014
Source: Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) [edited]
http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-11-27/poppy-seeds-mildew-outbreak/5921520


Poppy companies confirm mildew outbreak spread by infected seeds
----------------------------------------------------------------
Tasmania's poppy industry has confirmed they are fighting a new virulent and damaging mildew selectively attacking poppies. The mildew does not discriminate between poppy varieties and has been spread across Tasmania by infected seeds.

Fungicide trials to manage the spread of the mildew have failed and the only way to effectively control the spread of mildew next [2015] season is to identify and eliminate infected seeds.

The poppy industry says 'it can't afford to fail' and has flown in an international expert on systemic mildew. Professor Hermann Voglmayr says the new mildew that also exists in Europe, _Peronospora somniferi_, is highly infectious. "It is systemic, which means that the plant is totally infected at a young stage as a seedling," he said. "Because the disease is inside [the plant] you can't fight it with fungicides."

The disease is a more severe type of downy mildew [than the one] that already exists in Tasmania and is easily treated with regular fungicides.

Dr Voglmayr says eliminating infected seeds from breeding crops is the best way to manage future outbreaks. "In infected seeds the pathogen is already close to the plant when it germinates and can infect it. This can then cause big epidemics if the weather conditions are favourable." He says it would be pure speculation at this stage how it travelled from Europe to Tasmania.

[Byline: James Jooste]

